name: Catch the Wind
comments: This composition, written sometimes in the mid-1960s, was never recorded by Evans, nor given a title. The title “Catch the Wind” was born after a conversation between jazz vocalist Karen Gallinger and Nenette, Bill’s wife. According to Nenette, at Bill’s funeral their son Evan had said something like: “Mommy, daddy would be here if he could catch the wind”. Gallinger used that title for the formerly unknown song and wrote the lyrics with that in mind.

The title reflects the fact that the squatters renamed the building "Georg-von-Rauch-Haus“ after a leftist activist shot by police in 1971. Within the German squatter movement the song became a classic with the refrain "Das ist unser Haus“ (This is our house) being shouted out as a motto.

Proserpina
comments: The last work written Kate McGarrigle prior to her death in 2010. Her daughter, Martha Wainwright, recorded it for her 2012 Come Home to Mama album. The song is about the legend of Proserpina, an ancient Roman goddess whose story of being carried off to the underworld by Pluto, only for him to later agree she could spend nine months of the year with her mother, is the basis of a myth of springtime. The legend is interpreted as symbolizing the growth and decay of vegetation. Kate McGarrigle performed the song just once, at her last concert at Royal Albert Hall in December 2009.
